# transform from label to number
# This function is later used for one_hot_encoding of the image labels.

def tran(t):
    T={'B':0,
        'b':1,
        'K':2,
        'k':3,
        'Q':4,
        'q':5,
        'R':6,
        'r':7,
        'P':8,
        'p':9,
        'N':10,
        'n':11,
        'F':12}
        
    return T[t]

# transform from number to label
# This method is later used to generate the labels from numerical values.

def tran_t(t):
    T={0:'B',
       1:'b',
       2:'K',
       3:'k',
       4:'Q',
       5:'q',
       6:'R',
       7:'r',
       8:'P',
       9:'p',
       10:'N',
       11:'n'}
    
    return T[t]

Function for generating a FEN code from predicted labels

In [6]:
def make_name(y):
    str1=''
    count=0
    #This counter represent the empty spaces before any chess piece detected
    for n in range(64):
        if n!=0 and n%8==0:
            # This if statement is for row changes, when triggered,it adds a'-' in the name
            if count!=0:
                str1+=str(count)
            count=0
            str1+='-'
        if y[n]==12:
            # if 12:'F' (empty) is detected: counter++
            count+=1
        else:
            # if chess piece is detected
            if count!=0:
                str1+=str(count)
            count=0
            str1+=tran_t(y[n])
        if n==63 and count!=0:
            # the end of the name
            str1+=str(count)
    return str1+'.jpeg'

Our picture reading function for dividing the picture into 64 samll blocks

In [7]:
# '1b1B1b2-2pK2q1-4p1rB-7k-8-8-3B4-3rb3.jpeg' here we use this image as an example

def read_picture(name,location='train'):
    img = cv2.imread('input/chess-positions/dataset/'+location+'/'+name,cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE) 
    name_t=name.split('.')[0] 
    #Convert FEN code to labels
    # return '1b1B1b2-2pK2q1-4p1rB-7k-8-8-3B4-3rb3'
    po=name_t.split('-') 
    # get a list of size 8 with FEN code for each row of the chessboard
    # return ['1b1B1b2','2pK2q1','4p1rB','7k','8','8','3B4','3rb3']
    index=np.zeros((8,8))

    for n in range(8): # Go through every row.
        temp=[]
        for t in po[n]:
            if t>='1' and t<='8':
                for num in range(int(t)):
                    temp.append(int(12))
            elif t>='A' and t<='z':
                temp.append(tran(t)) # transform label to number
        index[n,:]=np.intc(temp)

    
   # Separate the image into 64 sections.
    size=50 
    # If a 400*400 image is divided into 64 parts, then each part has a size of (400/8)*(400/8) =50*50
    index2=np.zeros((64,size**2))
    for i in range(8):
        for j in range(8):
            index2[i*8+j,:]=np.array(img)[i*size:(i+1)*size,j*size:(j+1)*size].reshape(1,size**2)
    # index2 is a 64*2500 array, with each row as the pixel info of that 50*50 area
    
    y_1=np.zeros((64,13))
    y_1[range(64),index.reshape(1,-1)[0].astype('int64')]=1
    # this step, y_1 is a 64*13 array, each row represent the one_hot_encode form for that 50*50 area
    
    # Finally, return the index2 (the img info) and y_1(labels)
    return index2,y_1

Our CNN model. Here use the CNN model from Keras document CIFAR10-CNN. This model is used for CIFAR10. Every time we randomly select one picture from training set and divide it into 64 small blocks. To balance the number of sample of block with pieces and empty block every time we reduce the number of empty block to the same as the number of pieces. Then use the samples for training. This procedure will repeat 6000 times.

In [8]:
def model_build():
    
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), padding='same',input_shape=(50,50,1)))
    # As the core idea in this notebook is the feature detection and classification of the 50*50 pixel
    # sub-areas, thus the input shape here should be 50*50*1 (gray mode)
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(512))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    model.add(Dense(13))
    model.add(Activation('softmax'))
    
    # 'softmax' to classify 13 categories
    rms = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.00005, decay=1e-6)
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer=rms,metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

Time=[]
size=50
loss=[]
acc=[]
start=time()

cnn=model_build()

for ep in range(6000):
    # In total, this will trian with 6000 pictures
    chess=np.zeros((1,size**2))
    label=np.zeros((1,13))

    for name in sample(file,1):  #Randomly select one picture
        
        index2,y_1=read_picture(name,location='train')
        # Here, index2,y_1 can be seen as X_trian, y_train.
        
        #Balance the number of empty blocks and the pieces
        X_noempty=index2[y_1[:,12]==0] 
        y_noempty=y_1[y_1[:,12]==0]
        X_empty=index2[y_1[:,12]==1][0:len(y_noempty)//2,:]
        y_empty=y_1[y_1[:,12]==1][0:len(y_noempty)//2,:]

        chess=np.concatenate((chess,X_noempty,X_empty), axis=0)
        chess=chess/255 
        # Normalization of the pixel values, to eliminate the adverse effects caused by singular sample data.
        label=np.concatenate((label,y_noempty,y_empty))
        
    # Train CNN
    train_history=cnn.fit(chess[1:,].reshape(len(chess)-1,50,50,1), label[1:,], epochs=10, batch_size=10,verbose=False)

#Test on test set
y_res=[]
y_res_class=np.zeros((1,1))
y_ture=np.zeros((1,1))
for name in test:
# test all sample in the testing set

    chess2,y_1=read_picture(name,location='test')
    chess2=chess2/255
    # Normalization of the pixel values, to eliminate the adverse effects caused by singular sample data.
    
    y_pre=np.argmax(cnn.predict(chess2.reshape(len(chess2),50,50,1)),axis=1)
    y_res.append(make_name(y_pre))
    
    y_res_class=np.concatenate((y_res_class,y_pre[:,np.newaxis]))
    y_ture=np.concatenate((y_ture,np.argmax(y_1,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]),axis=0)
    
# Generate the classification report for evaluation
Classifi_R=classification_report(y_ture[1:,], y_res_class[1:,],output_dict=True)
A=np.mean(np.array(y_res)==np.array(test))


Time.append(time()-start)

print('Accuracy:',A)
print('Time used:',Time[0])
